Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

10:06 AM Defendant Vanessa L Elmhorst appeared by Zoom.  Attorney Pablo Galaviz in court for Vanessa L Elmhorst. District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Niki Kane. All parties have agreed that some may have the hearing conducted remotely. This hearing has met the statutory standards for video conferencing. The Court is in receipt of a compliance letter from WCS noting that the only thing found in the defendant's system was THC. The Court will modify the conditions of bail removing WCS but will add to the bond that after every in person appearance the defendant is required to go to WCS for drug testing. The defendant states she will come to the Courthouse today to sign her bond.
Hearing scheduled for October 24, 2022 at 01:30 pm.

10:24 AM District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Niki Kane. Defendant Vanessa L Elmhorst in court.  Attorney Pablo Galaviz in court for Vanessa L Elmhorst. 

The Court finds that the Defendant's waiver to a preliminary hearing is knowing and voluntary. 
Waive reading of Information. 
NOT GUILTY PLEA ENTERED.

10:24 AM District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Niki Kane. Defendant Vanessa L Elmhorst in court.  Attorney Pablo Galaviz in court for Vanessa L Elmhorst. 

The Court calls the matter for bail/bond hearing.
The Court notes that WCS filed a letter stating that the Defendant's new address does not qualify her for WCS as they don't monitor in the county the Defendant lives in. 
Attorney Galaviz concurs with the WCS letter.
The State does not take a position.
The Court orders the Defendant to go to WCS and be drug tested.  If the Defendant has positive screen the Court will issue a warrant.   If the Defendant has a negative screen the Court will take up the issue of WCS at the next date.  The Court will authorize Zoom for the next hearing if the Defendant has a negative screen.
Hearing scheduled for September 8, 2022 at 10:00 am.
